That is fine. In your current design, `userId` is already the stable shared identifier:

```text
AS400 GPS number:   GPS000001
Partner Repository: user_id = GPS000001
Ping/Keycloak user: preferred_username = gps000001
Arthur lookup:      findByUserId("gps000001")
```

The case difference is the only thing to watch:

```text
GPS000001
gps000001
```

PostgreSQL string equality is normally case-sensitive, so:

```java
findByUserId("gps000001")
```

will not find:

```text
GPS000001
```

unless your stored value is also lowercase.

Best fix: normalize the identifier consistently when receiving it from AS400 and when looking it up after authentication.

For example, use lowercase everywhere:

```java
private String normalizeUserId(String userId) {
    return userId == null ? null : userId.trim().toLowerCase(Locale.ROOT);
}
```

When saving AS400 data:

```java
String userId = normalizeUserId(
        request.getSource().getGpsGroupNumber());

user.setUserId(userId);
user.setUsername(userId);
```

When Arthur receives `preferred_username` from Ping:

```java
String userId = normalizeUserId(claims.getPreferredUsername());

UserResponse user = partnerRepositoryClient.getUser(userId);
```

Then your database contains:

```text
gps000001
```

and Ping also returns:

```text
gps000001
```

So `findByUserId(...)` works consistently.

Because you are already using `findByUserId`, you do not need `gpsGroupNumber` as a separate lookup key unless AS400 sends a different external identifier in the future. In that case, keeping `gpsGroupNumber` can still be useful for traceability, but it should contain the same normalized value.
